@node Requirements "zDir - Requirements"

                            zDir - Requirements


Normal usage and xDir-mode:
 ° An Amiga with kickstart V37 (2.04) or greater.

The Xtra option (-X[n]):
 ° xfdmaster.library V38 or greater (not included)
 ° + optionally FileID.library V7 or greater (not included)

The MultiUser option (-m):
 ° multiuser.library V39 or greater (not included)


  Note  that  while  zDir refuses to run on pre-V37 systems, it will simply
issue  a  warning  (and  ignore the offending option) if you have chosen an
option that requires xfdmaster.library, FileID.library or multiuser.library
without  having  it in your Libs: drawer. zDir will work fine without these
libraries  and  will  only  try  to  load  them  when told to do so via the
@{"options" Link Usage 56}.
@endnode

@node Usage "zDir - Usage and options"

                         zDir - Usage and options


 @{B}Usage:@{UB}

  Usage  is  simple,  just  use  zDir  like  most  other Dir-commands. Type
"zDir ?"  to  get  a  small  overview  of  the  options.  To  read  several
directories  just  put them after each other and zDir will read them one by
one,  if  you  don't  specify  any  directories  zDir will read the current
directory.  If  you  enter a name with spaces in it, you'll have to enclose
that name in single or double quotes or zDir will think that it's more than
a single name.
  Options  can  be anywhere on the command line and starts with a '-'. When
an '-' is encountered zDir will start parsing options. zDir accepts options
both the 'lha-style' like:

	zDir -loR mydir

  and the 'lzx-style' like:

	zDir -l -o -R mydir

  and mixed like

	zDir -lo -R mydir

  and even

	zDir -l mydir1 -o mydir2 -R

  Note  that  zDir  parses  all options before reading the directory(s) and
that  the  option(s)  specified last override the option(s) specified first
(except  for  the -C and -F options). All directories specified in the same
line  will  be  read  with  the  same options active. All options are case-
sensitive, so while "zDir -m" is ok, "zDir -M" will fail.

  To  read a directory where the name starts with a '-' or has spaces in it
just  enclose  the name in single or double quotes or use the -- option. If
you  get  the  'unknown option' error you probably just forgot to that, for
example:

	zDir -mydir

would fail because the exists no -y option, but all of these combinations

	zDir "-mydir"
	zDir '-mydir'
	zDir -- -mydir
	zDir -- "-mydir"
	zDir -- '-mydir'

would work.



 @{B}Options:@{UB}

  Here  is  the  list  of  all  zDir's  command line options. Note that the
command  line  options  are  all  case-sensitive  and  that all options are
toggles with some sideeffects (except the -C and -F options).


  --	stop option parsing

	  This  option  will stop all option parsing. This option *must* be
	followed by a space character.
	  Following  this option everything on the rest of the command line
	is assumed to be file- or directory-names.


  -l	List-mode

	  This switch turns on zDir's list-mode. In this mode zDir's output
	will  be  very similar to List only with a little nicer look and an
	extra field for extra information.
	  The extra information can be one of the following: "(Lnk)" if the
	entry  is not really a file or a directory but a hard- or soft-link
	to  one, "(Dir)" if the entry is a directory, "(XFH)" if entry is a
	file  that has an XFH-comment attached to it (XFH-comments will not
	be  shown)  and  finally  "(...)"  if the entry is just an ordinary
	file.
	  This cancels the -m, -n, -x, and -X[n] options.


  -L	List dates (list-mode)

	  Same  as  -l except the date field will always contain the date
	and  never  a  substitute such as "Yesterday", "Monday", "Future"
	etc. and -m is not turned off.
	  This cancels the -n, -x, and -X[n] options.
	  This always turns on the -l option.


  -c	ignore Comments (list-mode)

	  Same  as  -l  except  zDir will ignore all comments and -m is not
	turned off.
	  This cancels the -n, -x, and -X[n] options.
	  This always turns on the -l option.


  -m	MultiUser list (list-mode)

	  This  option turns on zDir's MultiUser-mode. When this is on zDir
	will   also  show  the  group  and  other  protection  bits  +  the
	owner/group  field. Note that the MultiUser 'u'-protection-bit will
	be shown in place of the AmigaDOS 'h'-bit. This always turns on the
	-l option.
	  If  multiuser.library V39+ isn't available this option is ignored
	(except for turning on the -l option).
	  This cancels the -n, -x and -X[n] options.


  -x	xDir-mode

	  This  switch  turns  on  zDir's xDir-mode. In this mode zDir will
	recognize  xpk-packed  and  powerpacked datafiles and will show you
	both  the  filesize and the origional/uncrunched size of the file +
	it  will  calculate  the  ratio  by which the file was crunched and
	inform you which packer was used.
	  This cancels the -l, -c, -n, -m, -d and -X[n] options.


  -X[n]	Xtra

	  Same  as  -x except in this mode also xfdmaster.library V38+ (and
	optionally FileID.library V7+) will be used to recognize files. The
	output format is a little different because xfd can't inform you of
	the  uncrunched filesize of all recognized filetypes (except if you
	really   uncrunch   the  file),  this  is  because  of  the  stupid
	fileformats of some lame crunchers.
	  The  n is optional and can be either 1, 2 or (the logical OR of 1
	and 2) 3, if n is 1 zDir will tell xfdmaster.library to enable it's
	external  libraries  to  recognize  files. If n is 2 then zDir will
	also use FileID.library (if it's available) to recognize files, and
	if n is 3 zDir will use both external slaves and FileID.
	  This  cancels  the  -l, -c, -n, -x, -d and -m options, however if
	xfdmaster.library V38+ isn't available zDir will fall back to using
	the -x option instead (in this case FileID won't be used either).


  -i	no disk Info

	  If  this  option  is  specified on the command line zDir will not
	print  out  it's  usual  disk information at the end of a directory
	listing.


  -p	no path

	  If  this option is specified, zDir will not print out the path of
	the directory read, this cancels -R.


  -n	only names

	  If  this  option is on, zDir will only print the names of entries
	in  a  directory,  not filesize or other information. This works in
	both  dir-mode and list-mode. If you also disable escape-codes zDir
	will  try  to append directory names with a '/' if there's room for
	it.  Note  that this is cancelled by -l, but does not itself cancel
	-l.
	  This cancels -m, -S, -x, -X and -c.


  -R	Recursive scan

	  This  option  tells  zDir  to  read  every  directory encountered
	recursively.
	  This cancels the -f, -d, -p and -S options.


  -f	only Files

	  This  option  tells  zDir to only show files. This option cancels
	the -S, -R and -d options.


  -d	only Dirs

	  This  option  tells  zDir  to  only show directories. This option
	cancels the -x, -X[n], -f, -S and -R options.


  -h	Hide 'hidden' entries

	  This  option tells zDir not to show files or directories that has
	the 'h'-bit (FIBF_HIDDEN) set. This cancels -a.


  -a	All

	  This option simply cancels -h and disables HIDE.


  -S	Sizecheck dirs

	  This  option  tells  zDir  to  recursively  scan  each  directory
	encountered  summing  up  all  the  filesizes.  If you also disable
	escape-codes  zDir will try to append directory names with a '/' if
	there's  room  for  it. Also in this mode the fields Files and Dirs
	will  display  the  total  number of files and dirs encountered and
	Size  includes  dirsizes.  In  this  mode  patternmatching  will be
	disabled.  This  option  cancels  the  -f, -d, -n, -x, -X[n] and -R
	options.


  -o	sOrting

	  This switch toggles wether zDir should sort all the names or not.
	This  is  useful  for  turning  on  sorting  in list/xdir-modes. By
	default  sorting is off in list/xdir-modes. Sorting is always on in
	dir-mode.


  -E	Escape-codes

	  This  switch  toggles wether zDir will output any escape-codes to
	the  console.  By  default zDir prints files in color 1 (black) and
	directories  in  color  3  (blue), but when redirecting output to a
	file it can be useful to turn escape-codes off.
	Also see the DIRPEN option.


  -F<pattern> : Find <pattern>

	  With  this  option  you  can  tell  zDir  to  recursively  scan a
	directory  for  a  particular  file  or directory which matches the
	pattern.  This  cancels all other options including HIDE except for
	-m, -E, -c and -i. This option can only be canceled by -C.


  -C<pattern> : find <pattern> in Comment

	  With  this  option  you  can  tell  zDir  to  recursively  scan a
	directory  for a particular file or directory who's comment matches
	the  pattern.  This cancels all other options including HIDE except
	for -m, -E and -i. This option can only be canceled by -F.



 @{B}Settings in the 'zDir' environment variable:@{UB}

  zDir also has a environment variable called (amazingly enough) 'zDir'. By
setting  this variable you can change some of zDir's default behaviour. Use
the  'Set' or 'SetEnv' command to set these. Local variables (Set) override
global  variables (SetEnv), so you can have different settings in different
shellwindows at the same time.

 Examples:
	Set zDir "columns=4 kb=50 mb=50"
	SetEnv zDir "kb 150"

  To save the settings use 'SetEnv' and then "Copy Env:zDir EnvArc:".

  If  there  are any faults in the zDir variable all settings in it will be
completely ignored.
  Here  follows  the list of options that are recognized in the environment
variable.  Environment  variable  options  are case-insensitive (unlike the
command line options).


  COLUMNS=<n>  and  WIDTH=<n>

	  COLUMNS  determines  how  many  columns  zDir  will  print  out a
	directory  in  when  in Dir-mode. The valid range is 2 thru 20, the
	default  is 3. WIDTH determines the width of the individual columns
	when in Dir-mode. The valid range is 11 thru 41, the default is 22.
	You can also specify the following "magic" numbers for COLUMNS:
	-1: zDir  will  automatically  adjust the columnwidth and number of
	    columns according to the width of the shellwindow and lenght of
	    file-   and   dir-names.   zDir   will  check  the  windowwidth
	    automatically.  WIDTH  will  be  the  default  windowwidth when
	    redirecting  output  to  a  file,  Valid  range is 77 thru 880,
	    default  is 77. When COLUMNS is -1 zDir will adjust the columns
	    so  that  each  column  is only as wide as the longest entry in
	    that column, this will not be done when COLUMNS is -2.
	-2: Same  as  -1,  but  file-  and  dir-columnwidth  isn't adjusted
	    independently.
	Any other  negative number: Same as -2 but WIDTH is again the width
	    of  the  columns  and  only  number of columns is automatically
	    adjusted.  -COLUMNS  is  the  default  number  of  columns when
	    redirecting output to a file.


  KB=<n> and MB=<n>

	  This  affects  only  the 'Dir size', 'Disk Size', 'Disk Used' and
	'Disk Free' fields and determines how many Kb/MB is required before
	shifting  to  that notation. For example setting 'kb=50' would mean
	that  there  would  have  to  be 50 Kb free on the disk before zDir
	would express the 'Disk Free' field in Kb's instead of in bytes.
	  Setting  these  values  to  0 or not setting them at all disables
	this feature.


  OPTS=-<opts>

	  This  allows you to specify some default options for zDir. <opts>
	are the same options that you can specify on the command line. When
	using  this  option zDir will interpret it almost as if the options
	were  the  first  thing on the command line, the only difference is
	that  the  -- option will always give an error and that the options
	given  here  *must*  be  specified  together  (use '-Eo' instead of
	'-E -o').
	  So  if the zDir variable is set to "OPTS=-Eo" the line 'zDir foo'
	will  be  interpreted  the  same as 'zDir -Eo foo' without the OPTS
	keyword.
	  If  the  options  are  not  prefixed  with  a '-' they are simply
	ignored.  That  is  'OPTS=Eo'  will be ignored, but 'OPTS=-Eo' will
	work.
	  This  option  is  mostly useful if you want sorting automatically
	turned  on  in  all  list-modes  and/or  you prefer that zDir never
	prints  any escape codes. You can also make zDir ignore comments in
	list-modes with 'OPTS=-cl'.
	  WARNING:  The  same routine is used to parse these options as the
	command  line options, this *will* allow you to set yourself up for
	getting  into trouble. For example specifying -f, -d, -F or -C here
	is asking for trouble.
	  In  some  cases  defining  an alias is better than using the OPTS
	keyword, examples of this are the -m, -x and -X options.


  COMPACT
	  When  this switch is specified zDir will output path and diskinfo
	in a more compact format.


  DIRPEN
	  This  is  the  pen  used  to  print directories in when -E is not
	specified.  Acceptable  values  are  0 thru 7, default is 3 (blue).
	Files are always printed with pen 1 (black).


  SEPLEN=<n>
	  The  argument determines the separator between names in dir-mode,
	it  can be 1 for a 1-space separator, 2 for a 2-space separator and
	3 (the default) for a space, a bar ("|") and a space.


  ALTDIR
	  This  switch causes zDir's dir-mode to display the sorted entries
	in an alternative way. That is, to read the entries in alphabetical
	order  you should read them one column at a time instead of one row
	at  a  time.  When  this  is used zDir will try to fill the columns
	instead  of  filling  the  rows  (but  still  in  as  few  lines as
	possible).


  HIDE=<pat>
	  This  is  any AmigaDOS pattern you want and specifies which files
	and  directories  to  hide.  Useful to hide icons (HIDE=#?.info) or
	hide  names  beginning with a dot (HIDE=.#?, like UNIX-ls) or maybe
	both  (HIDE=(.#?|#?.info).  Ofcourse  you  can also play a trick on
	your friends by setting it to #? :-).
@endnode

@node Install "zDir - Installation"

                            zDir - Installation


  To install zDir you only have to do the following:

 1. @{"(ACTION) Copy zDir to C:zDir" System "Copy zDir C:zDir"} to install zDir.
 2. @{"(ACTION) Protect C:zDir +p" System "Protect C:zDir +p"} to set the pure bit.
 3. If  you  use  the  Shell  a lot it is a good idea to make zDir resident
    during startup (insert "Resident C:zDir Add" in your @{"S:User-Startup" System "Ed S:User-Startup"}).
 4. Also  you'll  probably  want  to set some options in zDir's environment
    @{"variable" Link Usage 242}.

  It's that simple.


  I  myself have renamed C='s Dir to WBDir and copied zDir to C:Dir (that's
how much I trust it).
@endnode

@node History "zDir - History"
@next Author

                              zDir - History


V2.7 (13.2.98) - 'Friday the 13th' edition: 12512 bytes
  Managed to screw up -S with some of the changes in V2.6, fixed.
  The ALTDIR option sometimes caused Enforcer hits, fixed.
  The switch NOBAR changed to the numeric argument SEPLEN.
  zDir will no longer enter directory links recursively.
  When COLUMNS is -1 zDir will now adjust the columns so that each column
  is only as wide as the longest entry in that column.
  New environment variable option, HIDE, will hide any pattern you want.
  New option, -h, hides files with 'h'-bit (FIBF_HIDDEN) set.
  New option, -a, cancels -h and HIDE.
  Option parsing routine allowed a space between -F and -C and their
  argument, fixed.

V2.6 (30.12.97): 11532 bytes
  A  small  bug  found  in the output routine: by making the shellwindow to
  thin for a single column to be printed, zDir would go into a never-ending
  loop, that could only be broken by a CTRL-C, fixed. Minor optimizations.
  Four  new  options added by suggestion of Erik Spĺre: NOBAR and ALTDIR in
  the  environment  variable (NOBAR has been suggested before and now again
  by  Erik),  and  -p  for 'no path' and -n for 'only names' on the command
  line.
  Changed -S, now a '/' will only be appended to directory names when -E is
  also in effect.
  Reduced  the  size  of  guide  by  removing  all the crap about xpk, xfd,
  PowerPacker, MultiUser and FileID

V2.5 (14.10.97): 10848 bytes
  Removed  the  'Total'  count  from the normal (non-COMPACT) look (I guess
  people can add 'Files' and 'Dirs' themselfes) and replaced it with 'Size'
  (which used to be 'Dir size' from the -s option). As a consequence the -s
  option has also been removed. Shortened some strings.

V2.4 (10.10.97): 11096 bytes,  Not uploaded to aminet.
  zDir  will  now  automatically  check  the  width of the shellwindow when
  COLUMNS  is  a negative number, see the environment @{"variable" Link Usage 242} for info on
  this. Ups, forgot the bytesize in V2.3 history-entry, corrected now.
  Unfortunatly  I oploaded this version to a BBS before I decided to do the
  changes  to  V2.5,  so the version number had to be changed again for the
  full aminet release.

V2.3 (3.10.97): 10832 bytes
  The  environment  variabel  now  has two more options: COMPACT and DIRPEN
  (suggestion  of Phil Beazley). Reversed the history entries in the guide.
  Some minor optimizations done.

V2.2a (30.9.97): 10560 bytes,  Not publicly released.
  COLUMNS=-2  now  also  autoadjust  columnwidth  and number of columns pr.
  line,  but  files  and  dirs  are  adjusted  together (suggestion of Phil
  Beazley).

V2.2 (28.9.97): 10520 bytes
  You  can now make zDir automatically adjust the columnwidth and number of
  columns  according  to the lenght of file- and dir-names and width of the
  shellwindow  by  specifying  COLUMNS=-1  (thanks to Phil Beazley for that
  suggestion).
  Also  did  a few changes in the option parsing routine (combinations like
  -RS and -SR were broken).

V2.1 (22.9.97): 10228 bytes
  xfdmaster.library  V38  has  a  new  RECOGLEN  feature  (thanks to Stuart
  'Kyzer'  Caie  for  making  me  aware  of that). zDir has been updated to
  support that feature, therefore zDir no longer supports xfdmaster.library
  V37. To use  the -X option you now need xfdmaster.library V38 or greater.
  Use  xfd's  xfdLibInfo  to  see  which decrunchers currently support this
  feature.
  Some  redundancy  eliminated  (the  same  code appeared several times and
  parts  of  a  few  strings  could be reused). Also I'm now using strcpy()
  instead of stpcpy(). Thus V2.1 is actually *smaller* than V2.0.

V2.0 (16.8.97): 10368 bytes
  This  is  a  complete  rewrite  of  my  Dir-command,  featuring  loads of
  improvements  over  the  old  versions,  some of which are: more options,
  better  (ie.  faster)  sorting  algorithm  and support for xpk, xfd and
  MultiUser.
  Like   all  other  sensible  people  I  no  longer  program  for  pre-V37
  Kickstarts,  so  Kickstart  2.04 or greater is @{"required" Link Requirements} (but 3.x is even
  better).  Now  called "zDir" (the 'z' comes from "@{"zznyyd" Link Author}", my login name
  at @{"DIKU" Link DIKU}, and "zznyyd" comes from "ZzNyYd! Design.").

V1.0 - V1.42 (30.03.95): 4120 bytes
  Ancient  history.  V1.42  can  be  found  in  Aminet:util/cli/Req.lha, no
  previous  versions  have  been  publicly  released  (didn't have internet
  access  then).  V1.42  is the last version to support pre-V37 Kickstarts.
  All the V1.xx versions contain a small bug, causing them to refuse to run
  when Mungwall was running, this has been fixed in V2.0
@endnode

@node Ni "Ni - a revolution in CLI/Shell commands."
@next Ni
@prev Ni

                  Ni - a revolution in CLI/Shell commands

  ZzNyYd! Design now presents a revolution in CLI/Shell commands. A command
that  says  "Ni."  when  you  break  it.  Yes it's true: zDir says "***Ni."
instead  of  "***Break",  this  is  indeed  a revolutionary breakthrough in
CLI/Shell commands.

  So be warned, only break this command if you are not afraid of being said
'Ni'  to  (I  guess  then  you're  really,  really, really, really, really,
really,  really,  really,  really,  really, really, really, really, really,
really,  really,  really, really, really, really brave (like Sir Robin, the
brave knight :-)).


"We are the knights who say 'Ni'."
"It's a sad time when bullies can go around saying 'Ni' to old women."

	from "Monty Python and The Holy Grail" by Monty Python



DISCLAIMER:

I  take  absolutely no responsibility for any psychological effects, mental
illnesses  or  traumatizations  on  people  that zDir says 'Ni' to and will
under  no circumstances pay any following psychiatrist bill to get you back
on  your feet. In particular I take no responsibility for mentally unstable
people  who, upon being said 'Ni' to, shoots or kills other people or maybe
just goes into a coma.

Being  said 'Ni' to is the risk you have to take when breaking zDir. If you
can't handle such behaviour, do not try to break zDir.
@endnode

